segments.text: Hello everybody and welcome to the Great America Show.
Thanks for being with us as we pursue and protect truth, justice, and the American way.
High prices are dimming the outlook for our economy.
Inflation is in fact worsening and there is no end in sight for what is now clearly the onset of an inflationary cycle.
Food and energy prices are rising quickly and will of course be felt throughout the economy.
And those higher prices, if they don't ease, will slow the consumer demand and slow as well the overall economy.
The Biden White House ending the illegal immigrant expulsion policy that will bring an estimated 300,000
illegals into this country each month. Three and a half million in the next year alone.
This after two million illegals entered the United States and President Biden's first year.
And 1.6 million were released into our country.
White House Press Secretary Jen Psaki defended the President by claiming
Republicans are politicizing the border crisis.
While Psaki actually admitted the border is broken.
President Biden's poll numbers certainly aren't improving. 57% of those surveyed in the new
Rasmussen poll disapprove of the way he's doing his job as president.
64% say the country is headed in the wrong direction.
Not good for President Biden and not good for the Democrats.
Here with us today is the former Speaker of the US House of Representatives,
Newt Gingrich. No one better credential to address our national politics and American governance.
Newt is also a best-selling author. In fact, his newest book will be out in June. It's entitled
Defeating Big Government Socialism. And you can pre-order your copy now.
I recommend all of Newt's books. His website is Gingrich360.com for all things.
Gingrich. Newt is also a podcaster, historian, and great American.
Newt, first of all, it's a great honor to have you with us here on the Great America Show.
And I'm just fascinated to hear your summarization of where the Republican Party is right now.
A lot of talk about red waves. And then some talk about we must be cautious. Your thoughts.
Well, look, I don't think you can ever take anything for granted.
I think that right now all the patterns tend to favor the Republicans.
I would be very, very surprised if we didn't have Kevin McCarthy as the Speaker of the House next
year because they only need to pick up five seats. And I've given the current data. They're more
likely to pick up 40 than they are to pick up five. So I'm pretty confident about the House.
And I think frankly, the Senate's starting to get in better and better shape. I mean, Nevada,
for example, the Democrats are just collapsing because things aren't working between high
gasoline prices, high food prices, and the impact of the governor's mistakes in COVID.
You have, in Nevada, I think some 10,000 workers at the resorts who are still unemployed.
Well, they're not very excited about the job the Democrats have done.
And so you actually see Latinos in Nevada now breaking Republican and very big numbers,
something which is truly historic. So I think overall, this could be a great year. I think,
you know, it's at least in part a great year because the combination of, I think, three things,
the personalities, I mean, you have between Biden, Harris, Schumer, Pelosi, people who are just
not very desirable as leaders. And in the House, the top three House members on the Democratic side
are so old that their collective age would be would take you back to 1777, 10 years before the,
the Constitution was adopted. I mean, so people look at that and it's one thing to be older and
succeed. But if you're older and you're not succeeding, they sort of compound.
I think second, there's a plain out performance problem. You know, we've had Hillary and Barack
Obama both say, oh, it's a messaging problem. Well, when you're out there and you're filling up
your gas tank, I, I filled up a Calistas car the other night and it was $91. Now at $91,
there's no messaging that makes you feel good. You go to the grocery store and I got the price of
beef or the price of chicken. Wheat is going to go up dramatically this year because the Ukraine
is a very, very big wheat producer. And the fact is that you have about 40% of the world's
wheat supply comes from Russia and Ukraine. So you're going to have huge pricing impacts there.
Those are the kind of things you have to think about that are all coming together as a performance
problem. And then lastly, you have a plain out values problem. When you start talking to people
and you ask them, you know, do you really think that three-year-olds ought to be,
ought to be involved in discussing transgender issues? They think you're not, I mean, the average
American doesn't get where the left is on all these cultural things. So I think those three things
all come together in a way which is stunningly destructive.
This is really a battle cry right now from, from Middle America. Is the Republican party in your
judgment being strong enough on the issue? Are they building this into their national campaign? I
realized we're talking about a midterm, but a national campaign because it seems such a compelling
issue. Well, I think it's growing as an issue. And you see the reaction, for example, to
the bill that Governor DeSantis got passed in Florida that says that you can't discuss it
before, you know, until they get out of the third grade. Well, you know, 84% of the country believes
parents ought to have the right to know what's happening in their child's school. So just start
with that. I mean, and I think you'll see that become a national Republican position
all across the country that you as a parent have a right to know what teachers are doing with
your children. And of course, the teachers union is bitterly opposed to that.
Naturally, and the teachers unions for the first time in my career are actually in the focus of
the public and blaming them for much of what has occurred as a result of COVID in the way in which
they responded by closing down schools, insisting that they be protected in quotes.
It's really a strange moment that this should be happening right now. Your thoughts on that issue?
Well, I think you have this whole motion. And I think you're exactly right that you have
people who first of all go to these woke universities and then they end up teaching.
And their values are radically different than the values of the parents.
And, you know, it turned out, for example, not only do 84% of the country think that
parents have every right to know what is being taught their children, but an equal 84% believe
that America is worth fighting for. There are values and principles are worth fighting for.
Well, you know, if you're a left winger who's anti-American, these things are just anatomically
you. And so there is a real potential fight between the parents and those who believe in
defending America and the teachers union and its more radical members.
And radical members galore most funding of political campaigns and candidates from
the two major teachers unions overwhelmingly goes to Democrats. That in and of itself is a
tremendous statement about what needs to be done to assure local control of public education.
Don't you think? Well, I think that's exactly right. And what you end up with is a situation where,
you know, I think one at every four delegates at the last Democratic Convention was for the
teachers union. And so in a sense, they're a the Democrats are kind of a wholly owned subsidiary.
And if you look at the people who lead the teachers union, they're all hardline left winners.
The post office has six public employee unions. The federal government is unionized for crying
out loud. State governments unionize county and so forth throughout the country and without
without public employee unions. Well, that's right. And you end up in a situation, I think,
that when you're you're dealing with the average American for a very long time, we just assumed
that the teachers were normal that you could trust them. I mean, you know, there's a certain
building on psychological need, right, to be able to say, you know, that I'm sending much
out to somebody I can trust. And now I think one of the side effects of people staying home
and the schools going to distance learning was all of a sudden parents learned
what what in fact was happening in their schools. And I think they were shocked.
I think that's a great point because it also taught us a lot about maybe we could reclaim some
decentralization in our lives, whether it's going into work, whether it is simply trying to build up
a life at home in your neighborhood, in your community, when many people were spending most
of their time committing back and forth through work. I think that's right. And I think, you know,
we're going through so many different changes right now. And we're going to be so disrupted
by things like inflation, crime, millions of illegal immigrants. I mean, the degree to which
the left has has broken down the system. People like George Soros putting in millions of dollars
to elect pro criminal anti victim, district attorneys, some of whom are by any reasonable
standard certifiably crazy, who people who would put rapists and murderers and carjackers back on
the street. You know, I think I think the country is taking a measure of this. And then the country
doesn't find it very acceptable. So I think there's a chance here that you may be about to have
literally an American majority, much bigger than a Republican majority. And you may be about to have
people, anti left Democrats, independents and Republicans, all coming together. And that would
really be a remarkable moment.
Yeah. And that moment may be upon us. One of the numbers that I think doesn't get enough attention
again, certainly in the media is the number of independents who are responding in the affirmative
when they talk about Republicans and the in the midterm elections. They're obviously,
for the first time, overwhelmingly moving toward the Republican Party. How important is that in
your judgment? Well, I think what you're seeing is the Democratic Party beginning to be crowded back
into being sort of woke college professionals who are isolated from the whole rest of the country.
And the very interesting book called Coming Apart, which looked at by Charles Murray,
who looked at the zip codes and said, there are a set of zip codes in the US where people who went
to Harvard, Princeton, Yale, Stanford, etc. marry people who go to Harvard, Princeton, Yale, Stanford.
And those zip codes are totally different from the whole rest of the country.
Right. And when, you know, it's a fascinating small book. And I happened to read it during the
rise of Trump in 2016. And I would tell reporters, you know, if the apprentice had been on PBS and
had followed Del Nabi, you would understand why he's so good. But the fact is that because he was
on commercial television, none of you watched it. None of you saw the apprentice, none of you had
any idea what he was like. And it was just, you know, and I think that this is something you see
happening. So for a long time, the woke college graduates were held up by Latinos and by African
Americans and others. But increasingly, the working mind, the ethnic minority working group,
the people actually go out every day in their living. They're looking at gas prices,
they're looking at food prices. They're listening to these weird ideas. They don't want their kids,
you know, they don't want their daughters in a bathroom with some guy who's claiming to be a girl.
They don't want to see their, their show, their daughter lose a swimming match to some guy who's
clearly male, etc. And so what you end up with is a very deep desire by growing number. I think
we may actually get a majority of the Latino vote and about 30% of the African American vote this
year. And that's really a remarkable change. That would be truly a dramatic and historic change.
With those numbers that high, the Democratic Party would be on the edge of the abyss, wouldn't they?
Well, look, I think there's a chance if Republicans can really think about being
the American majority party and can really reach out to independents and to disaffected Democrats,
which is what Reagan did so brilliantly, bring them all together. I think you could see a new
governing majority emerge, particularly if after they win, they keep their word, they find ways to
be helpful. You know, this was sort of what Reagan did in the 80s. I'm actually beginning to
write some newsletters at Gingrich 360. I'm going to write a series of four newsletters on the concept
of creating a American majority rather than a Republican majority. And if that happens,
then you have ended the the rose of Elte and majority after 90 years. And you've really changed
fundamentally how this country is going to solve its problems.
Well, I can't wait to read your thoughts on that. But give us a bit of a prelude, if you will,
because the right now the left controls every aspect of our lives and point of fact, business,
government, education, media, I can't think of a sinkhole quarter where the left. And in many
cases, excuse me, in most cases, there are Marxists left us. It is it's hard to envision
there being a quick sudden reshaping of the body politic.
Well, I look at it. You put your finger on one of the great challenges. I keep on my desk the
1093 page book that Heritage produced called Mandate for Leadership, which they did for Reagan in
1980. They brought in 250 experts. They outlined how to reshape the federal government very
dramatically. Reagan came into office, picked up the book, hired all these people. And there's a
famous scene in the in the cabinet room where Ed Meece puts the book on the table and says,
this is our plan. I mean, it was just, you know, and so they were able to really take over the
government. We need the same depth of thinking now. We need to recognize that whether it's the
Pentagon or health and human services or the Department of Education, all of these large,
creaky old bureaucracies infiltrated and infested by left-wingers who have contempt for the voter
and contempt for elected officials and frankly contempt for the law. That's all going to have to
be cleaned out. And unless we're prepared to do that, we're not going to be capable of really
turning the corner. You know, you can win one election on bad performance, but you can't build
a majority in the long run just on bad performance. Well, Donald Trump was, I think,
just a historic leader. I know one since Reagan had had his impact. No one since FDR and my judgment
had done as much in terms of domestic policy as he did in four years in their first four years.
I'm all for that. And I am about as anti-establishment as any Republican can be, I believe.
But I don't know where you turn in academia. That's what is my point because-
Well, you may just have to turn to smart business people. I mean, frankly, I'd rather have a smart
conservative football coach than have a dumb left-wing college professor.
Okay. Well, I take your point. And my point again is that right now we are bereft of real talent
in either social criticism or conservatism itself in academia. Why is that?
Well, that's because I get crowded out because the other side understood that they were totally
committed to driving everybody out of public life that didn't cow-tow and agree with them.
And it's almost a Maoist groupthink model. And I think you just have to recognize that. So our
job is to go out and to find people of the courage to stand up. You'll find them in individual places,
you'll find them in some of the think tanks, you'll find them in businesses, you'll find them in
Republican state governments. My guess would be if you and you know, he might not want you to do
it. But if you went down to Florida, the DeSantis has gotten 50 or 100 really smart people running
the Florida state government. It really does. DeSantis is- he is a phenomenon, isn't he?
He really is. I would say that other than Trump, he is the most exciting and most interesting
person that I have seen come along from a Republican side. And I think that he
clearly has a great national future. He's also got $100 million in his war chest for re-election,
which is assured. So that becomes- do you think he's going to be running irrespective of what
the president's on? Well, I suspect he might be. I think you look at- I always tell people,
it's a long way from here to 2024. At this point in 2014, nobody would have thought Donald Trump
was even going to run. Right. I want to talk too about just the system, because of all that- if
the Republican party has the wisdom to follow your guidance and your thinking,
your architecture for what should be done, if indeed the red wave builds and comes crashing
down on the polls on Election Day, what is to assure us that the electoral system
won't be rigged just as it was in 2020? Oh, I think first of all that a lot of states have adopted
rules that make it much harder that they learn from it. I think I would say to everybody who's
concerned that they should see the great new film from Citizens United called rigged, which is-
was about basically what Zuckerberg did with $415 million. So I think in that sense,
if you watch rigged, you'll understand that a lot of the elections setup occurred long before
the election, that the left was determined to methodically defeat Trump by any means they had to.
It's an incredible- I think it's the best documentary that David Bossy has produced. He's
he's done some great documentaries, but this is so clearly and so entertainingly
elucidates what actually happened, particularly in the three battleground states- Arizona,
Wisconsin, and Georgia- 42,000 votes, 10,000 in Arizona, 11,000 in Wisconsin, and and 2021,000,
22,000 you could argue the point, but it comes out to 42,000 among three states that made the
difference in the outcome of that election. That means something should have been done because
if it's rigged, it isn't right, is it? No, that's right. Now, I think, look, if you're an average
everyday American and you don't have a spare billion dollars, clearly you had billionaires
trying to take control of the country, and you had Google and Facebook and Twitter cheating by
every- any reasonable standard. I mean, when you take the President of the United States off of
social media, and you're and you're denying it and it gets 73 million votes,
you have to ask yourself, you know, by what right? What's their moral authority?
For for denying the President's access. When you take the oldest newspaper of the United States
and the fourth largest newspaper of the United States, the New York Post, and you cut it off
of social media because it is accurately reporting on Hunter Biden's corruption, something which
now even the New York Times and Washington Post are finally admitting to two years later.
You know, there's something sick about how the left was cheating and what the left was doing.
And to suggest that all of that happened, as pure happened stance and coincidence that
the timing was, if not, it was contemporaneous. It was simultaneous in most instances and point of
fact, the New York Times and the Washington Post, though, to their discredit, have not
acknowledged their responsibility and the consequences of that decision to cover up for Joe Biden and
the laptop. It's disgusting. And as you point out, there's a number of events had they been
controlled. Had William Barr had the guts as he knew Joe Biden was lying in that debate,
to have said, excuse me, I think it's important that we point out that this is an active investigation,
that this is a real laptop. And those 50 Intel officers are simply not aware of the reality.
He considered that intervention had he done that. Meanwhile, he also acknowledges that Joe Biden
lying is an intervention of itself. What do you think?
Well, I mean, first of all, I think that the, when the Republicans take over that the intelligence
committee has to really dive into the profound dishonesty of over 50 leading figures in the
intelligence community, signing a letter which is totally false. I mean, there's something really
sick about people who are trusted by the American people because they were seen as senior intelligence
people. And they, and they all collectively lied. So from that standpoint, I think there's a lot
that has to be done. And I think it's also a reminder that most of these bureaucracies are
left wing. Most of these bureaucrats are quite prepared to cheat and that you, you have to really
understand how much they are committed to defeating Trump no matter what and know how many laws they
broke. I thought it was truly remarkable. The way in which the underlying professionals,
the FBI, the CIA, the Justice Department, they were all cheating. And it's just remarkable.
I don't remember any time in American history that it was like this. And it was a dramatically bigger
than anything that we saw happening in Watergate. I mean, you look at the stupidity of Watergate
and then you look at this stuff and you can tell that there was just no comparison
about the way in which this operated. There's sort of a reflex on the part of some to say about the
FBI. When I say, you know, they're cheating, they're crooked, and that's the way it is.
There's no if-ends-butts. It's unequivocal. And they'll say, yes, but there are good people within it.
And then I'll say the CIA, the same thing, but there are good people. What strikes me, Newt, is
there may be good people in it, but not a single damn one, stacked up and expressed himself or
herself in favor of the American people in just simple decency and honesty.
That's exactly right. I mean, you're in a situation where you're being told
that these are really honorable people, but in fact, their honor didn't come to insisting on the
truth or breaking from the group. And my question then goes to the very simple
matter of what next should we do about the Republican Party itself. You mentioned Kevin McCarthy.
He in the minds of many is rather weak to be the leader. He attacked the president right after
January 6. He's bowed down to the January 6 committee and has been too often very, I'll put it this
way, flexible with the Democratic leadership. Yeah, I mean, I guess I'm having been speaker. I
guess I see it somewhat differently. McCarthy opposed the committee refused to assign any
Republicans to serve on it and has consistently attacked it. But the house is a place where if
you have 218 votes, you can just run over people. So I think under the rules of the house,
Pelosi had certain advantages. And she used him, but he didn't collaborate with her. If anything,
he's been very tough. And I think you're going to see when he is in a position to
wield power that he will be, you know, there's going to be some significant payback in the
road. He has been. I mean, look, look what he did in terms of of Liz Cheney, who, you know,
was supposed to use, she was in the leadership. She was in the number three position in the
leadership. And then boom, she wasn't. Yeah. And she was censured, if you will. But
why not just expel her from the party after what she had done? There's just an attitude within
the house. I mean, what McCarthy has done to just stay with him for a minute is he has openly
endorsed and raised money for her opponent. Right. And then it said, you know, we ought to beat
her. She shouldn't come back. I think their view was that if they kicked her out of the party while
she was still serving, Nancy would just appoint her to something else. And she would become, you know,
would you further prove that inside the house right now, the speaker has power, which is, in fact,
how the house works? Well, the house members that I've spoken with are concerned that he has,
in point of fact, not been strong enough, not loud enough on issues that matter,
including the impeachment of the president twice. He has not been loud enough when it comes to
the January 6th Committee and the laptop, why in the world with this in front of him? Is there
not a Republican investigation of it? I think you do have Republicans who are raising Kenya,
Republicans who are, you know, trying to pressure the Justice Department. And I think that you'll find
that the morning that they control the house, that they will, in fact, be organizing a whole
series of those kinds of investigations. I mean, I'm not quite sure what it is they would do
right now because they don't technically have the legal ability to, they can't go out and
subpoena anybody. They certainly talk about it a lot. And I think that's...
I guess what I'm saying, Nude, is I would like to see if they could
gin up nothing other than public education. It would be extremely helpful to the party.
It would also show that there's some grit and gristle to them that isn't really very apparent
right now. They got outsmarted in 2020. This with President Trump saying as early as May,
their election was rigged, and the RNC did nothing. I can't tell you how many times I talked with
the RNC and officials who assured me that they had all the people on the ground, that they needed,
they had all the attorneys that were ready to go. They were going to be at every polling station,
and they're going to be diligent and energetic. None of it happened. It was a pathetic performance
on the, again, on the part of the RNC. And in 2016, Trump had won despite the RNC.
So what are we to do? I mean, I watched last year, for example,
and Youngkin did a write, and they had 4,000 people as poll watchers,
and they got a pretty honest count. And they got the state to agree that all the absentee ballots
would be counted first. So they didn't have any ability to go back to the absentee ballots and say,
you know, gee, we need another couple of thousand because they don't even count it and block down.
And I think that's a model for the future. I do think all of us, I include me in this,
I had no idea how much. And then this is part of why Bossy's movie couldn't be made
any faster because they had to get these various reports filed. And they legally didn't have to
be filed till the end of the year. But once you look at the, follow the money, it is staggering
how big an effort that was. And I think all of us, in that sense, were caught flat-footed. I mean,
we just never occurred to us. But somebody would go out here and spend $415 million
on the election directly through city governments in a way that clearly is totally corrupt. And I
think, you know, I will speaking for myself, I was certainly caught flat-footed.
But what happened in five cities in Wisconsin with the, what amounted to according to Gableman,
the Michael Cableman, the Special Counsel investigating it and still investigating it,
you know, it was election bribery straight out. I think that's right.
And it was bribery then, it's bribery now. And that's a felony. Yet nobody has
per the prosecuted. The Bill Barr again, the Attorney General had every responsibility
and obligation to investigate and did not. It was a perfect storm of indolence,
incompetence, and meat, lily-livered elected officials and appointed officials. Couldn't have
happened at the worst time for the people or for the president.
Well, and I think that it illustrated just how viciously and totally the establishment was
dedicated to blocking the American people from having an honest election.
Yeah, I think that's exactly right. And I'm sure that we're going to see that red wave
you speak of. And I know that the Democrats are going to do everything they can to
rest victory from the jaws of defeat. You want to give us your sense of what you think the outcome
will be in November? And I know it's early days. If I were guessing,
we'll probably be plus four in the Senate. And I think we'll be somewhere between 40 and 70 in the
house. From your lips to God's ears. New Gingrich, it's great to have you with us. We appreciate it
so much. It's always terrific. And I look forward to doing it again, Lou. New Gingrich,
great American. And I really like his midterm election prediction.
Tomorrow, our guest will be Congresswoman Claudia Taney. She's a conservative. She's smart and a
fighter for truth, justice and the American way. You'll like her a lot. Please join us. We want to
invite you to sign up for our great America show advisory and newsletter. Simply go to ludabs.com
that's ludabs.com and click on the email newsletter button. It's as simple as that. And we'll send
you our advisories and alerts as well as our weekly newsletter. I don't want to overstate
anything, but I'm pretty sure you will absolutely sense at least a small positive change in your
world outlook. We invite you to join us and stay in touch. Thank you. That's ludabs.com.
Thanks. God bless you and God bless America.
